            "content": "{\n  \"files\": [\n    {\n      \"repo\": \"rust-lang/rust\",\n      \"path\": \"library/core/src/task/wake.rs\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"repo\": \"rust-lang/rust\",\n      \"path\": \"library/core/src/task/poll.rs\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"repo\": \"rust-lang/rust\",\n      \"path\": \"library/core/src/future/future.rs\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"repo\": \"rust-lang/rust\",\n      \"path\": \"library/core/src/future/poll_fn.rs\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"symbols\": [\n    {\n      \"repo\": \"rust-lang/rust\",\n      \"path\": \"library/core/src/task/wake.rs\",\n      \"symbol\": \"RawWaker\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"repo\": \"rust-lang/rust\",\n      \"path\": \"library/core/src/task/wake.rs\",\n      \"symbol\": \"RawWakerVTable\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"repo\": \"rust-lang/rust\",\n      \"path\": \"library/core/src/task/wake.rs\",\n      \"symbol\": \"Waker\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"repo\": \"rust-lang/rust\",\n      \"path\": \"library/core/src/task/wake.rs\",\n      \"symbol\": \"LocalWaker\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"repo\": \"rust-lang/rust\",\n      \"path\": \"library/core/src/task/wake.rs\",\n      \"symbol\": \"Context\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"repo\": \"rust-lang/rust\",\n      \"path\": \"library/core/src/task/wake.rs\",\n      \"symbol\": \"ContextBuilder\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"repo\": \"rust-lang/rust\",\n      \"path\": \"library/core/src/task/poll.rs\",\n      \"symbol\": \"Poll\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"repo\": \"rust-lang/rust\",\n      \"path\": \"library/core/src/future/future.rs\",\n      \"symbol\": \"Future\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"repo\": \"rust-lang/rust\",\n      \"path\": \"library/core/src/future/poll_fn.rs\",\n      \"symbol\": \"PollFn\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"chain\": [\n    {\n      \"repo\": \"rust-lang/rust\",\n      \"path\": \"library/core/src/task/wake.rs\",\n      \"symbol\": \"RawWaker::new\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"repo\": \"rust-lang/rust\",\n      \"path\": \"library/core/src/task/wake.rs\",\n      \"symbol\": \"RawWakerVTable::new\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"repo\": \"rust-lang/rust\",\n      \"path\": \"library/core/src/task/wake.rs\",\n      \"symbol\": \"Waker::wake\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"repo\": \"rust-lang/rust\",\n      \"path\": \"library/core/src/task/wake.rs\",\n      \"symbol\": \"Waker::wake_by_ref\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"repo\": \"rust-lang/rust\",\n      \"path\": \"library/core/src/task/wake.rs\",\n      \"symbol\": \"Waker::from_raw\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"repo\": \"rust-lang/rust\",\n      \"path\": \"library/core/src/future/future.rs\",\n      \"symbol\": \"Future::poll\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"repo\": \"rust-lang/rust\",\n      \"path\": \"library/core/src/future/poll_fn.rs\",\n      \"symbol\": \"poll_fn\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"text\": \"The Rust async runtime waker mechanism is primarily implemented in the core library's task and future modules. The fundamental components are:\\n\\n1. **RawWaker and RawWakerVTable (library/core/src/task/wake.rs)**: These types form the low-level mechanism for task wakeup. RawWaker contains a data pointer and a reference to a static RawWakerVTable, which is a virtual function pointer table defining clone, wake, wake_by_ref, and drop operations. This allows custom executor implementations to provide their own wakeup behavior without heap allocation.\\n\\n2. **Waker (library/core/src/task/wake.rs)**: A high-level wrapper around RawWaker that is Send and Sync. The Waker type encapsulates a RawWaker and provides safe methods like wake() and wake_by_ref() for waking up tasks. It delegates the actual wakeup behavior to the underlying RawWaker's vtable functions.\\n\\n3. **LocalWaker (library/core/src/task/wake.rs)**: Similar to Waker but without Send/Sync bounds, allowing non-thread-safe data types to be used as waker data. Both Waker and LocalWaker can be constructed from RawWaker instances using from_raw().\\n\\n4. **Context (library/core/src/task/wake.rs)**: The execution context passed to Future::poll(). It provides access to the current Waker and LocalWaker for the task, allowing futures to store the waker and call wake() when they become ready to make progress.\\n\\n5. **ContextBuilder (library/core/src/task/wake.rs)**: A builder for constructing Context with both Waker and LocalWaker support.\\n\\n6. **Poll enum (library/core/src/task/poll.rs)**: Represents the result of polling a future - either Poll::Ready(value) or Poll::Pending. This type is returned by Future::poll().\\n\\n7. **Future trait (library/core/src/future/future.rs)**: The core async abstraction with a poll() method that takes a Context and returns Poll<Output>. This is the fundamental interface that drives the polling loop in async runtimes.\\n\\n8. **poll_fn utility (library/core/src/future/poll_fn.rs)**: Provides PollFn struct and poll_fn() function for creating futures from custom polling functions, demonstrating how the polling mechanism works with custom logic.\\n\\nThe polling loop flow: An executor repeatedly calls Future::poll() with a Context containing a Waker. If a future returns Poll::Pending, it must store a clone of the Waker and call wake() on it when ready. When wake() is called, it invokes the RawWakerVTable's wake function, signaling the executor to poll the future again.\"\n}\n",
